Time Model Statistics

  • DB Time represents total time in user calls
  • DB CPU represents CPU time of foreground processes
  • Total CPU Time represents foreground and background processes
  • Statistics including the word "background" measure background process time, therefore do not contribute to the DB time statistic
  • Ordered by % of DB time in descending order, followed by Statistic Name

Finding 2: Checkpoints Due to Parallel Queries
Impact is 1.63 active sessions, 32.31% of total activity.
---------------------------------------------------------
Buffer cache writes due to concurrent DML and parallel queries on the same
objects had a significant impact on the throughput of the I/O subsystem.

   No recommendations are available.

   Symptoms That Led to the Finding:
   ---------------------------------
      Wait class "Application" was consuming significant database time.
      Impact is .33 active sessions, 6.62% of total activity.


Finding 3: Undersized SGA
Impact is 1.02 active sessions, 20.19% of total activity.
---------------------------------------------------------
The SGA was inadequately sized, causing additional I/O or hard parses.
The value of parameter "sga_target" was "13312 M" during the analysis period.

   Recommendation 1: Database Configuration
   Estimated benefit is .65 active sessions, 12.8% of total activity.
   ------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Increase the size of the SGA by setting the parameter "sga_target" to
      16640 M.

   Symptoms That Led to the Finding:
   ---------------------------------
      Wait class "User I/O" was consuming significant database time.
      Impact is 1.4 active sessions, 27.8% of total activity.


Finding 4: Free Buffer Waits
Impact is 1.01 active sessions, 19.92% of total activity.
---------------------------------------------------------
Database writers (DBWR) were unable to keep up with the demand for free
buffers.

   Recommendation 1: Database Configuration
   Estimated benefit is 1.01 active sessions, 19.92% of total activity.
   --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Consider increasing the number of database writers (DBWR) by setting the
      parameter "db_writer_processes". Also consider if asynchronous I/O is
      appropriate for your architecture.
   Rationale
      The value of parameter "db_writer_processes" was "1" during the analysis
      period.
   Rationale
      The value of parameter "disk_asynch_io" was "TRUE" during the analysis
      period.

   Recommendation 2: Host Configuration
   Estimated benefit is 1.01 active sessions, 19.92% of total activity.
   --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate the I/O subsystem's write performance.
   Rationale
      During the analysis period, the average data files' I/O throughput was 0
      K per second for reads and 0 K per second for writes. The average
      response time for single block reads was 0 milliseconds.

   Recommendation 3: Application Analysis
   Estimated benefit is 1.01 active sessions, 19.92% of total activity.
   --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate application logic for possible use of direct path inserts as
      an alternative for multiple INSERT operations.

   Symptoms That Led to the Finding:
   ---------------------------------
      Wait class "Configuration" was consuming significant database time.
      Impact is 1.05 active sessions, 20.69% of total activity.

-------------------------------------------------------

   Recommendation 1: Host Configuration

      online redo log files.

      all other activity.

      Impact is .46 active sessions, 9.16% of total activity.

         WITH
         contratos_com_parcela AS (
         SELECT c.num_conta
         FROM   arreconline.parcela p
         join arreconline.contrato c ON p.id_contrato = c.id
         GROUP  BY c.num_conta
         ),
         agendamentos AS (
         SELECT ac.num_conta
         FROM   agpbd.agendamento_complemento AC
         join agpbd.agendamento_debito AD ON AC.id_agendamento =
         AD.id_agendamento
         join agpbd.agendamento A ON AC.id_agendamento = A.id
         join agpbd.debito D ON AD.id_debito = D.id
         WHERE  D.ativo = 1 AND A.id_situacao = 1 AND Nvl(A.valor_pago, 0) <
         A.valor_debito
         ),
         carteira AS (
         SELECT *
         FROM   contratos_com_parcela
         UNION
         SELECT *
         FROM   agendamentos
         )
         SELECT CS.id,
         CS.cpf,
         CS.agencia,
         CS.conta,
         CS.valor_agrupado,
         CS.id_tipo_credito_consolidado,
         CS.id_credito_situacao,

         CS.data_registro,
         CS.saldo_disponivel,
         Nvl(O.mantem_salario, 1) AS CLIENTE_MANTEM_SALARIO,
         DECODE(C.num_conta, null, 1, 0) AS SEM_CARTEIRA,
         (SELECT D.HISTORICO FROM ARRECONLINE.CREDITO D WHERE ROWNUM = 1 AND
         D.ID_CREDITO_CONSOLIDADO = CS.ID) AS HISTORICO
         FROM   arreconline.credito_consolidado CS
         join arreconline.operacao O ON O.id = CS.id_operacao
         left join carteira C ON CS.conta = C.num_conta
         WHERE  CS.id_credito_situacao = :situacaoCreditoConsolidado

Finding 7: Free Buffer Waits
Impact is .25 active sessions, 5.92% of total activity.
-------------------------------------------------------
Database writers (DBWR) were unable to keep up with the demand for free
buffers.

   Recommendation 1: Database Configuration
   Estimated benefit is .25 active sessions, 5.92% of total activity.
   ------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Consider increasing the number of database writers (DBWR) by setting the
      parameter "db_writer_processes". Also consider if asynchronous I/O is
      appropriate for your architecture.
   Rationale
      The value of parameter "db_writer_processes" was "1" during the analysis
      period.
   Rationale
      The value of parameter "disk_asynch_io" was "TRUE" during the analysis
      period.

   Recommendation 2: Host Configuration
   Estimated benefit is .25 active sessions, 5.92% of total activity.
   ------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate the I/O subsystem's write performance.
   Rationale
      During the analysis period, the average data files' I/O throughput was 0
      K per second for reads and 0 K per second for writes. The average
      response time for single block reads was 0 milliseconds.

   Recommendation 3: Application Analysis
   Estimated benefit is .25 active sessions, 5.92% of total activity.
   ------------------------------------------------------------------

   Symptoms That Led to the Finding:

      Wait class "Configuration" was consuming significant database time.

         WITH
         contratos_com_parcela AS (
         SELECT c.num_conta
         FROM   arreconline.parcela p
         join arreconline.contrato c ON p.id_contrato = c.id
         GROUP  BY c.num_conta
         ),
         agendamentos AS (
         SELECT ac.num_conta
         FROM   agpbd.agendamento_complemento AC
         join agpbd.agendamento_debito AD ON AC.id_agendamento =
         AD.id_agendamento
         join agpbd.agendamento A ON AC.id_agendamento = A.id
         join agpbd.debito D ON AD.id_debito = D.id
         WHERE  D.ativo = 1 AND A.id_situacao = 1 AND Nvl(A.valor_pago, 0) <
         A.valor_debito
         ),
         carteira AS (
         SELECT *
         FROM   contratos_com_parcela
         UNION
         SELECT *
         FROM   agendamentos
         )
         SELECT CS.id,
         CS.cpf,
         CS.agencia,
         CS.conta,
         CS.valor_agrupado,
         CS.id_tipo_credito_consolidado,
         CS.id_credito_situacao,
         CS.id_operacao,
         CS.data_registro,
         CS.saldo_disponivel,
         Nvl(O.mantem_salario, 1) AS CLIENTE_MANTEM_SALARIO,
         DECODE(C.num_conta, null, 1, 0) AS SEM_CARTEIRA,
         (SELECT D.HISTORICO FROM ARRECONLINE.CREDITO D WHERE ROWNUM = 1 AND
         D.ID_CREDITO_CONSOLIDADO = CS.ID) AS HISTORICO
         FROM   arreconline.credito_consolidado CS
         join arreconline.operacao O ON O.id = CS.id_operacao
         left join carteira C ON CS.conta = C.num_conta
         WHERE  CS.id_credito_situacao = :situacaoCreditoConsolidado

Finding 4: Session Connect and Disconnect
Impact is .62 active sessions, 17.27% of total activity.
--------------------------------------------------------
Session connect and disconnect calls were consuming significant database time.

   Recommendation 1: Application Analysis
   Estimated benefit is .62 active sessions, 17.27% of total activity.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate application logic for possible reduction of connect and
      disconnect calls. For example, you might use a connection pool scheme in
      the middle tier.


Finding 5: Unusual "Other" Wait Event
Impact is .59 active sessions, 16.51% of total activity.
--------------------------------------------------------
Wait event "Failed Logon Delay" in wait class "Other" was consuming
significant database time.

   Recommendation 1: Application Analysis
   Estimated benefit is .59 active sessions, 16.51% of total activity.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate the cause for high "Failed Logon Delay" waits. Refer to
      Oracle's "Database Reference" for the description of this wait event.

   Recommendation 2: Application Analysis
   Estimated benefit is .59 active sessions, 16.51% of total activity.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate the cause for high "Failed Logon Delay" waits in Module
      "JDBC Thin Client".

   Recommendation 3: Application Analysis
   Estimated benefit is .59 active sessions, 16.51% of total activity.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate the cause for high "Failed Logon Delay" waits in Service
      "SYS$USERS".

   Symptoms That Led to the Finding:
   ---------------------------------
      Wait class "Other" was consuming significant database time.
      Impact is .59 active sessions, 16.54% of total activity.


Finding 6: Undersized SGA
Impact is .23 active sessions, 6.55% of total activity.
-------------------------------------------------------
The SGA was inadequately sized, causing additional I/O or hard parses.
The value of parameter "sga_target" was "13312 M" during the analysis period.

   Recommendation 1: Database Configuration
   Estimated benefit is .17 active sessions, 4.63% of total activity.
   ------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Increase the size of the SGA by setting the parameter "sga_target" to
      14976 M.

   Symptoms That Led to the Finding:
   ---------------------------------
      Wait class "User I/O" was consuming significant database time.
      Impact is 1.64 active sessions, 45.9% of total activity.


Finding 7: Commits and Rollbacks
Impact is .13 active sessions, 3.76% of total activity.
-------------------------------------------------------
Waits on event "log file sync" while performing COMMIT and ROLLBACK operations
were consuming significant database time.

   Recommendation 1: Host Configuration
   Estimated benefit is .13 active sessions, 3.76% of total activity.
   ------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate the possibility of improving the performance of I/O to the
      online redo log files.
   Rationale
      The average size of writes to the online redo log files was 31 K and the
      average time per write was 4 milliseconds.
   Rationale
      The total I/O throughput on redo log files was 0 K per second for reads
      and 752 K per second for writes.
   Rationale
      The redo log I/O throughput was divided as follows: 0% by RMAN and
      recovery, 100% by Log Writer, 0% by Archiver, 0% by Streams AQ and 0% by
      all other activity.

   Symptoms That Led to the Finding:
   ---------------------------------
      Wait class "Commit" was consuming significant database time.
      Impact is .13 active sessions, 3.76% of total activity.


Finding 8: Free Buffer Waits
Impact is .08 active sessions, 2.36% of total activity.
-------------------------------------------------------
Database writers (DBWR) were unable to keep up with the demand for free
buffers.

   Recommendation 1: Database Configuration
   Estimated benefit is .08 active sessions, 2.36% of total activity.
   ------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Consider increasing the number of database writers (DBWR) by setting the
      parameter "db_writer_processes". Also consider if asynchronous I/O is
      appropriate for your architecture.
   Rationale
      The value of parameter "db_writer_processes" was "1" during the analysis
      period.
   Rationale
      The value of parameter "disk_asynch_io" was "TRUE" during the analysis
      period.

   Recommendation 2: Host Configuration
   Estimated benefit is .08 active sessions, 2.36% of total activity.
   ------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate the I/O subsystem's write performance.
   Rationale
      During the analysis period, the average data files' I/O throughput was 0
      K per second for reads and 0 K per second for writes. The average
      response time for single block reads was 0 milliseconds.

   Recommendation 3: Application Analysis
   Estimated benefit is .08 active sessions, 2.36% of total activity.
   ------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate application logic for possible use of direct path inserts as
      an alternative for multiple INSERT operations.

   Symptoms That Led to the Finding:
   ---------------------------------
      Wait class "Configuration" was consuming significant database time.
      Impact is .08 active sessions, 2.36% of total activity.
